388	<h2><strong>About Zipline</strong></h2>\n<p>Do you want to change the world? Zipline is on a mission to transform the way goods move. Our aim is to solve the world’s most urgent and complex access challenges by building, manufacturing and operating the first instant delivery and logistics system that serves all humans equally, wherever they are. From powering Rwanda’s national blood delivery network and Ghana’s COVID-19 vaccine distribution, to providing on-demand home delivery for Walmart, to enabling healthcare providers to bring care directly to U.S. homes, we are transforming the way things move for businesses, governments and consumers. The technology is complex but the idea is simple: a teleportation service that delivers what you need, when you need it. Through our technology that includes robotics and autonomy, we are decarbonizing delivery, decreasing road congestion, and reducing fossil fuel consumption and air pollution, while providing equitable access to billions of people and building a more resilient global supply chain.</p>\n<h2><strong>About You and The Role </strong></h2>\n<p>Are you a systems thinker who thrives on bridging the gap between features and the real world? Do you love building software that ships across thousands of autonomous aircraft and enables life-saving deliveries? At Zipline, we’re building the future of logistics—and we’re looking for a Staff Software Integration Engineer who is passionate about making autonomy work at scale.</p>\n<p>This role is all about integration. You’ll be the person who takes a high-level feature—say, autonomous emergency landing or package retrieval —and makes it real. You’ll work across disciplines, from embedded autonomy to cloud orchestration, to stitch together the end-to-end implementation and ensure it’s validated, performant, and debuggable in the field. You’ll build tools, telemetry, and test strategies that help us deliver faster and more reliably, with confidence that what works in simulation works in flight.</p>\n<p>You’ll have a wide impact, deep technical ownership, and the satisfaction of seeing your work operate every day in the physical world—serving people who depend on it.</p>\n<h2><strong>What You'll Do </strong></h2>\n<ul>\n <li>Lead the <strong>end-to-end integration</strong> of complex, cross-functional features—from concept to deployment—ensuring alignment across autonomy, embedded software, backend systems, and operations.</li>\n <li><strong>Architect and develop</strong> vehicle and mission management aircraft software in Rust</li>\n <li>Develop infrastructure and tooling that support scalable integration, flight testing, and in-field debugging.</li>\n <li>Translate high-level requirements into detailed software interfaces and implementation plans, focusing on reliability, testability, and observability.</li>\n <li>Define system-level telemetry and performance metrics that allow Zipline to monitor and improve feature behavior in real time.</li>\n <li>Collaborate closely with autonomy engineers, flight operations, test teams, and hardware engineers to ensure features are both technically sound and operationally viable.</li>\n <li>Mentor other engineers on best practices and contribute to building a culture of ownership and cross-functional collaboration.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2><strong>What You'll Bring </strong></h2>\n<ul>\n <li><strong>10+ years of professional experience</strong> developing software for hardware products in a safety-critical field, e.g. aerospace, robotics, medical devices, autonomous vehicles</li>\n <li>Expertise in writing safety critical code in one or more of: Rust, C++, C</li>\n <li>Demonstrated technical leadership in a production environment, writing software that runs on complex autonomous systems that operate in the real world</li>\n <li>Demonstrated success in <strong>integrating cross-functional features</strong> into production systems—ideally in autonomous vehicles, drones, or industrial robotics.</li>\n <li>Deep experience in system-level testing, triage, and validation, including familiarity with <strong>SIL/HIL environments</strong>.</li>\n <li>Experience building real-world robotics systems and handling the long-tail corner cases to ensure high uptime systems</li>\n <li>Ability to manage technical ambiguity, break down complex projects, and drive them to completion with minimal oversight.</li>\n <li>Passion for enabling others—whether through great tooling, clear documentation, or thoughtful debugging support.</li>\n <li>Must be eligible to work in the US.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><strong>WHAT ELSE YOU NEED TO KNOW </strong><strong> </strong></h3>\n<p>This will be a hybrid role based out of our South San Francisco HQs.</p>\n<p>The starting cash range for this role is <strong>$210,000 - $265,000</strong>. Please note that this is a target, starting cash range for a candidate who meets the minimum qualifications for this role. The final cash pay for this role will depend on a variety of factors, including a specific candidate's experience, qualifications, skills, working location, and projected impact. The total compensation package for this role may also include: equity compensation; overtime pay; discretionary annual or performance bonuses; sales incentives; benefits such as medical, dental and vision insurance; paid time off; and more.</p>\n<p>Zipline is an equal opportunity employer and prohibits discrimination and harassment of any type without regard to race, color, religion, age, sex, national origin, disability status, genetics, protected veteran status, sexual orientation, gender identity or expression, or any other characteristic protected by federal, state or local laws or our own sensibilities.</p>\n<p>We value diversity at Zipline and welcome applications from those who are traditionally underrepresented in tech. If you like the sound of this position but are not sure if you are the perfect fit, please apply!</p>		https://jobs.techstars.com/companies/zipline/jobs/5